{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0c2a836-6900-4ee8-ad99-3fca4cefaf49","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**Line 3** — `datetime.now()` — This is a hard-coded static call that makes the view **untestable** because you can't control the returned time in tests.\n\n### Recommended fix\n\nUse Django's `django.utils.timezone.now()` instead, which is monkeypatchable, and inject or mock it in tests:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThis lets you freeze time in tests with libraries like `freezegun` or `unittest.mock.patch`:\n\n```python\nfrom unittest.mock import patch\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\nwith patch('django.utils.timezone.now', return_value=some_fixed_dt):\n    response = index(request)\n```\n\nThat single file is the only Python file in `my_app/` — no other untestable statics (`date.today()`, `time.time()`, `uuid.uuid4()`, `random.*`) were found.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65d14763-1d4b-4671-b69a-d9cd777801b7","outputTokens":264,"requestId":"A03C:3346ED:1CC32E6:20DA0D2:69FEA247"},"id":"d38be5bd-0f5d-45b4-b2a9-647ac317c0ea","timestamp":"2026-05-09T02:56:13.830Z","parentId":"27c8496c-1d83-4c57-8812-c9eb37ec2fce"}
